# Sheet1 ("Production List") — Complete Specification

> **Audience:** Any AI agent, developer, or maintainer working on these VBA macros.
> **Workbook:** `Production List_MM_dd_yy.xlsm` — a daily production tracking sheet for **Wilde Signs**, a sign manufacturing company.
> **Sheet name:** `Sheet1` (the only data sheet; `Sheet2` exists but is unused).

---

## 1. High-Level Purpose

Sheet1 is the single source of truth for every active work order at Wilde Signs. Each work day a new copy of the workbook is SaveAs'd with the next workday's date. Macros pull data from employee tally sheets, scan Outlook for approvals, look up proof files, check print-station completion, and move rows between sections as jobs progress through the production pipeline.

---

## 2. Row Layout

### Rows 1–3: Header Band

| Row | Content |
|-----|---------|
| **1** | `A1` = workbook date (formatted `dddd, mmmm dd, yyyy`). `B1` may hold a label or value used as a paste source (tally transfer copies `srcWs.Cells(1,2)` into col E). `C1` = list subtitle (e.g., `"(Shipping List)"` on shipping copies). |
| **2** | Column headers / formula seeds. `L2` and `M2` hold formulas that auto-fill downward (see columns L & M below). |
| **3** | Column headers row. Copied to printing sub-lists as their header row. |

### Row 4 onward: Data Begins

All data rows start at **row 4**. Every macro that reads, writes, or iterates the sheet starts at row 4.

---

## 3. Vertical Sections (Row Blocks)

The sheet is divided into **named section blocks** identified by marker text in **column A**. Rows are inserted *below* these markers and sorted within each block. The macros use `Find()` on column A to locate these markers at runtime — their row numbers are not fixed.

The sections appear in this top-to-bottom order:

| # | Column A Marker Text | Purpose | Sort Key |
|---|---------------------|---------|----------|
| 1 | `CUSTOMER` | Jobs shipping today / tomorrow. (TodayRowsMoveAndSort moves rows here from Coming Up when their Must Ship date arrives.) | Col A ascending |
| 2 | `MONTHLY` | Monthly/recurring orders divider. | — |
| 3 | `COMING UP…` *(with Unicode ellipsis U+2026)* | Approved jobs awaiting production. Rows land here from the tally pull when the proof is approved (`col E = "Approved"` or `"No"` in source). MoveAndSortRows also moves approved-Design rows here. | Col A ascending |
| 4 | `FLIP SIGNS & FABRICATION` | Marks the bottom boundary of the Coming Up block (used for sort range). | — |
| 5 | `Harmony Brands INV Orders/FoF PO's` | Harmony/HH Global inventory orders. HarmonyPull inserts `(INV)` category rows here. | Col A ascending |
| 6 | `DESIGN; PRODUCTION/ACTUAL ORDERS` | Active design/production work orders. New tally rows with `col E = "Yes"` land here. MoveAndSortRows moves rows *out* of this block into Coming Up once they receive an approval date in col H. | Col A ascending |
| 7 | `DESIGN; DESIGN ONLY ORDERS` | Design-only jobs (no production). Tally rows with `col D = "(DESIGN ONLY)"` land here. | — |
| 8 | `OUTSOURCED` | Outsourced jobs. Tally rows with `col D = "(OUTSOURCED)"` land here. | — |
| 9 | `INSTALL READY/DELIVERY/SHIPPING/INVOICING` | Completed/shipping/install jobs. InstallMove cuts rows from above and pastes them here when the shipping list marks them complete. | — |
| 10 | `ON-HOLD` | On-hold jobs. Also acts as a boundary: the shipping list copy (`CreateListShipping`) copies rows 4 through the row *above* this marker. | — |

### How Row Movement Works

```
Tally sheets ──► DESIGN; PRODUCTION/ACTUAL ORDERS  (or COMING UP / OUTSOURCED / etc.)
                         │
                   (approval date appears in col H)
                         ▼
                     COMING UP…
                         │
                   (Must Ship date ≤ next workday)
                         ▼
                      CUSTOMER
                         │
                   (shipping list marks complete)
                         ▼
              INSTALL READY/DELIVERY/SHIPPING/INVOICING
                         │
                   (strikethrough + archived)
                         ▼
                    Archive.xlsx
```

